Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Original Transcript (52 pages) PLEA AND SENTENCING, commencing 9/16/16, received and filed.
Bail Refund Packet
Corrected to show, Bail applied.

Defendant Laquan E Wilson in court with attorney Michael Jude.  Defendant Laquan E Wilson in custody.  Daniel j Gabler appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant sworn.  

Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, and plead GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Stipulation by parties to complaint as a factual basis to sustain the plea.  Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen, deportation is possible.  Court found the defendant guilty. Judgment of conviction entered.  Firearms warning given.  Voting admonishment given.  DNA notification given.  Any issues of restitution will be determined at sentencing.  

SENTENCE IS CONCURRENT TO CASE 16CF1823 AND CONSECUTIVE TO ANY OTHER SENTENCE.  

State complied with victim notification.  Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, Defense, and Defendant.   

The Court sentenced the defendant to a TOTAL LENGTH of imprisonment of 6 years.
The INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prisons is 2 years with credit for 146 days time served.
The Court orders the defendant to serve a maximum term of EXTENDED SUPERVISION of 4 years.

Conditions of Extended Supervision to be determined by the Dept. of Corrections, but to include:

*Mental health assessment and comply with any treatment deemed necessary by the department.
*Alcohol and drug assessment and comply with any treatment deemed necessary by the department.
*Absolute sobriety.
*Random urine screens.  No positive results.
*No illegal drugs.
*No controlled substances without valid prescription.
*No contact with drug community.
*No contact with the victim Kiara R. or her family and 7030 W. Carpenter Ave., Greenfield. 
*Seek and maintain full time employment.
*Obtain high school diploma or GED.
*Cognitive Behavior Therapy.

Restitution is ordered in the amount of $550.00 to be paid to Kiara R.

- DNA sample and DNA surcharge is mandatory and assessed if not already done.
- Defendant advised that he may never again possess firearms or weapons.
- Civil rights suspended until reinstated.  Order received and filed.

- Defendant does qualify for the Challenge Incarceration Program and does qualify the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program after serving 1 year initial confinement in cases 16CF1823 and 16CF21.

Appeal rights given.
